Kuni no miyatsuko governed small territories ({{Nihongo|kuni|国|}}), although the location, names, and borders of the provinces remain unclear. Kuni no miyatsuko were appointed by and remained under the jurisdiction of the Yamato Court, but over time the position became hereditary.<ref name="dijitaru">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Dijitaru daijisen |title=国造 (Kuni no miyatsuko) |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-04-12 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=ja |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 |df= }}</ref><ref name="encyclopedia">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Japan |title=Kuni no miyatsuko |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-04-12 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 |df= }}</ref> Kuni no miyatsuko carried [[kabane]] honoric names bestowed by the Yamato Court, commonly "kimi" or "atae". Prestigious Kuni no miyatsuko were called "omi".<ref name="encyclopedia"/>

==Taika Reform==

The office of kuni no miyatsuko was abolished in the [[Taika reforms]] in 645 and the former administrative ‘’kuni’’ provinces were formally reorganized under the [[ritsuryō]] system. The provinces became ruled by new officials called {{Nihongo|kuni no mikotomochi||}}, or more commonly, {{Nihongo|[[Kokushi (officials)|kokushi]]|国司}}.<ref name="encyclopedia"/> The kuni no miyatsuko continued to be appointed after the Taika Reform, generally to the office of {{Nihongo|gunji|郡司|}}.<ref name="dijitaru"/> Gunji were appointed from powerful regional kuni no miyatsuko families, appointed for life, and the position became heriditary.<ref name="dijitaru-gunji">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Dijitaru daijisen |title=郡司 (Gunji) |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-04-12 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=ja |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 |df= }}</ref> The Kuni no miyatsuko were now in charge of spiritual and religious affairs, specifically the [[Shintō]] rites of each province.<ref name="encyclopedia"/> These religious officials became known as {{Nihongo|shin-kokuzō|新国造|}}, or "new" kuni no miyatsuko.<ref name="encyclopedia"/> The kuni no miyatsuko, now in the office of gunji, often sided with peasants against the ruling kokushi elite. The gunji position, however, was abolished with the establishment of the shōen system in the early Heian period.<ref name="dijitaru-gunji"/> A few kuni no miyatsuko clans retained influence after the Taika reform, such as the {{Nihongo|Izumo no Kuni no miyatsuko|出雲国造}} of [[Izumo Province]] in present-day eastern [[Shimane Prefecture]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) (日本大百科全書(ニッポニカ) |title=Izumo Kuni no miyatsuko (出雲国造) |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-04-12 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=ja |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/w