The office of ''kuni no miyatsuko'' was abolished in the [[Taika Reform]]s in 645 and the former administrative ''kuni'' (provinces) were formally reorganized under the ''[[Ritsuryō]]'' system. The provinces became ruled by new officials called ''kuni no mikotomochi'', or more commonly, [[:en:Kokushi (official)|''kokushi'']].<ref name="encyclopedia"/> The ''kuni no miyatsuko'' continued to be appointed after the Taika Reforms, generally to the office of {{Nihongo|gunji|郡司|}}.<ref name="dijitaru"/> ''Gunji'' were appointed from powerful regional ''kuni no miyatsuko'' families, for life, and the position became hereditary.<ref name="dijitaru-gunji">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Dijitaru daijisen |title=郡司 (Gunji) |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-04-12 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=ja |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 }}</ref> The ''kuni no miyatsuko'' were now in charge of spiritual and religious affairs, specifically the [[Shinto|Shintō]] rites of each province.<ref name="encyclopedia"/> These religious officials became known as {{Nihongo|shin-kokuzō|新国造|}}, or "new" ''kuni no miyatsuko''.<ref name="encyclopedia"/> The ''kuni no miyatsuko'', now in the office of ''gunji'', often sided with peasants against the ruling ''kokushi'' elite. The ''gunji'' position, however, was abolished with the establishment of the manorial ''[[shōen]]'' system in the early [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]].<ref name="dijitaru-gunji"/> A few ''kuni no miyatsuko'' clans retained influence after the Taika Reforms, such as the {{Nihongo|[[Izumo clan|Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko]]|Izumo Province 造}} of [[:en:Izumo Province|Izumo Province]] in present-day eastern [[Shimane Prefecture]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) (日本大百科全書(ニッポニカ) |title=Izumo Kuni no miyatsuko (Izumo Province 造) |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessda